= Preparing Semantic Data Specification Version Release (on the Conceptual Model repository)

In the third stage, the https://docs.acceptance.ted.europa.eu/epo-wf/SDS%20and%20related%20artefacts/SDSmodel2owl.html#_sds_formal_artefacts:~:text=SEMIC%20style%20guide.-,SDS%20formal%20artefacts,-The%20ePO%20Semantic[Semantic Data Specification (SDS) formal artefacts] and some of the SDS documentation artefacts are generated by an automated process on the develop branch of the https://github.com/OP-TED/epo-conceptual-model[ OP-TED/ePO-conceptual-model] repository using the model2owl tools that use the Conceptual Model .xmi file as input. After the xref:../../SDS and related artefacts/SDSmodel2owl.adoc[artefacts] are reviewed, they are moved to the release branch of the Conceptual Model repository.

The stage can be further divided into two substages: Part 1, that describes the generation of the SDS artefacts, and part 2, that describes the review process of the SDS artefacts.

=== SDS Generation substage[[SDSGen]]

image::3.1.png[]
_The SDS Generation substage_

In the “*Initiate SDS release*” Business Process the Development Team enables a “light” code freeze on the develop branch in order to create the SDS artefacts and review them. This code freeze only allows modifications to the conceptual model in order to fix bugs discovered during the “Dev Team internal review”, "Dev Team Conceptual Model visual representation review", “Product Owner internal review (CM repository)” and "Product Owner internal review (ePO repository)" Business Processes, and no new features should be implemented.

In the “*Produce the interchange format of the conceptual model*” Business Process, the Development Team exports an .xmi file containing all the UML concepts including classes, attributes, properties, notes, etc., found in the diagrams of the Conceptual Model (editable) Business Object. The .xmi file shall be used as an input for model2owl toolkit in order to generate the SDS artefacts. Currently the version of the XMI/UML that is being exported is 2.5.1. The .xmi file is placed into the model2owl input folder on the develop branch of the https://github.com/OP-TED/epo-conceptual-model[OP-TED/epo-conceptual-model] repository and is represented as the “Conceptual Model (exchangeable)” Business Object on the workflow diagram. Once the .xmi file is pushed on the repository, model2owl will automatically begin generating all the SDS artefacts. In order to simplify this artefact generation we divide it into 4 business processes:

* Generate compliance checking artefacts
* Generate diffing artefacts
* Generate formal artefacts
* Generate human-readable artefacts

In the “*Generate compliance checking artefacts*” Business Process, model2owl generates the UML conventions reports for each model (represented in the diagram as the “Quality assessment reports” Business Object) on the develop branch of the https://github.com/OP-TED/epo-conceptual-model[ OP-TED/epo-conceptual-model] repository. These reports include SHACL shape checking of the formal artefacts, and possibly other types of checks.

For more information on the Quality assessment reports, read the xref:SDS and related artefacts/SDSmodel2owl.adoc#P3[documentation here].


In the “*Generate diffing artefacts*” Business Process,model2owl generates diffing reports, and change notes by comparing the current version .xmi, with the previous published version of SDS. Deprecated concepts are also generated by that comparison but are contained in the Lightweight Ontology (for interoperability) Business Object. For dealing with deprecation, refer to xref:Business Process workflow/stage2/stage2.adoc[] for more information. Specifically, the following Business Objects are generated on the develop branch of the https://github.com/OP-TED/epo-conceptual-model[OP-TED/epo-conceptual-model] repository:

. Change Notes
. SDS diffing report.

For more information on the diffing artefacts, read the xref:SDS and related artefacts/SDSmodel2owl.adoc#P4[documentation here].

In the “*Generate formal artefacts*” Business Process, model2owl generates the following SDS artefacts (listed as Business Objects) on the develop branch of the https://github.com/OP-TED/epo-conceptual-model[OP-TED/epo-conceptual-model] repository for a given module, using the “Conceptual Model (exchangeable)” Business Object (.xmi) as input:

. Lightweight Ontology (for interoperability) Business Object ( .rdf/.ttl ontology files).
. Ontology Axiomatization (for inference) Business Object. ( .rdf/.ttl restriction files).
. Application Profile (for interoperability) Business Object (SHACL shapes file).


For more information on the SDS artefacts, read the xref:SDS and related artefacts/SDSmodel2owl.adoc#P1[documentation here].

In the “*Generate human-readable artefacts*” Business Process, model2owl generates the “SDS reference document (glossaries)” Business Object, and possibly other human-readable reference documentation artefacts on the develop branch of the https://github.com/OP-TED/epo-conceptual-model[OP-TED/epo-conceptual-model] repository.
For more information on the SDS documentation artefacts, read the xref:SDS and related artefacts/SDSmodel2owl.adoc#P2[documentation here].

=== SDS Review substage

image::3.2.png[]
_The SDS Review substage_

In the “*Dev Team internal review*” Business Process, The Development Team reviews all Objects generated in this stage for any given module. Specifically:

. The Quality assessment reports (convention reports).
. The Diffing reports.
. The Formal artefacts (including metadata)
. The SDS reference documents (Glossaries).

The Development Team also makes sure that all GitHub Issues with a milestone of the upcoming release are implemented. If any errors or bugs are encountered, the Development Team fixes these errors by re-doing all the business processes of the Workflow from the “ORSD consolidation” Business Process, to the “Dev Team internal review” Business Process. Note that during this fixing of errors the “ePO Working Group Meeting” Business Process is omitted since the changes to the Ontology are purely technical. However, if there is a problem in the conventions this might require the WG to confirm what was meant by the wrong convention to allow it to be corrected.


In the “*Produce Conceptual Model visual representation*” business process, the Development Team exports an .html page for each folder in the Enterprise Architect (including the folder of the new ePO module) creating the “Conceptual Model visual representation” Business Object on the develop branch of the https://github.com/OP-TED/epo-conceptual-model[OP-TED/epo-conceptual-model] repository. This .html export can be done automatically by the Enterprise Architect program as seen in the figure below. The.html files will be reviewed by the Development Team and the Product Owner in their respective business processes later in this stage.
In the next stage, “publishing candidate SDS version” the .html pages will be integrated into https://github.com/OP-TED/epo-docs[OP-TED/epo-docs] repository and from there published in the TED developer documentation website.


image::data:image/png;base64,[]
_Publish HTML versions in EA_


In the "*Dev Team Conceptual Model visual representation review*" Business Process, the Development Team reviews  the "Conceptual Model visual representation" Business Object.  If any errors or bugs are encountered, the Development Team fixes these errors by re-doing all the business processes of the Workflow from the “ORSD consolidation” Business Process, to the “Dev Team internal review” Business Process. Note that during this fixing of errors the “ePO Working Group Meeting” Business Process is omitted since the changes to the Ontology are purely technical. However, if there is a problem in the conventions this might require the WG to confirm what was meant by the wrong convention to allow it to be corrected.

In the "*Dev Team pull request to Release branch*" Business Process, the Development Team does a pull request in order to merge the develop branch of the https://github.com/OP-TED/epo-conceptual-model[OP-TED/epo-conceptual-model] to the specific release branch release/X.Y.Z of the same repository. For more information on the creation of the release/X.Y.Z branch see xref:Business Process workflow/stage1/stage1.adoc[])

In the “*Product Owner internal review (CM repository)*” Business Process, In the context of the pull request mentioned in the "Dev Team pull request to Release branch" Business Process above, The Product Owner reviews all Objects generated in this stage for a given module. Specifically:

. The Quality assessment reports (convention reports).
. The Diffing reports.
. The Formal artefacts (including metadata).
. The SDS reference documents (Glossaries).
. The Conceptual Model visual documentation (HTML pages).

Regarding the Formal artefacts, the Product Owner should make sure that the following properties have the correct values, as seen on the image below: Specifically:

* dcterms:description should have a description of the specific module.
* dcterms:issued should have the correct date.
* dcterms:title should have the correct module name.
* rdfs:label should have the same value as that of dcterms:title.
* dcterms:created should always have the following value:
    "2021-06-01"^^xsd:date ;
* dcterms:license should always have the following value:
    "© European Union, 2014. Unless otherwise noted, the reuse of the Ontology is authorised under the European Union Public Licence v1.2 (https://eupl.eu/)." ;
* dcterms:publisher should always have the following value:
    "http://publications.europa.eu/resource/authority/corporate-body/PUBL" ;
* vann:preferredNamespacePrefix should always have the following value: "epo" ;
* vann:preferredNamespaceUri should always have the following value:
    "http://data.europa.eu/a4g/ontology#" ;
*  rdfs:comment should have the correct issue date and the correct module name.

* rdfs:seeAlso should always have the following value:
    <https://docs.ted.europa.eu/home/index.html>, <https://github.com/OP-TED/ePO/releases>, <https://joinup.ec.europa.eu/collection/eprocurement/solution/eprocurement-ontology/about>, <https://op.europa.eu/en/web/eu-vocabularies/e-procurement> ;
* owl:imports should include all the imports on the beginning of the file.
* owl:incompatibleWith should have any ePO versions that are not backward compatible with the current version.
* owl:priorVersion should have the previous published versions of the module.
* owl:versionIRI and owl:versionInfo should have the current versions of the module.




image::data:image/png;base64,[]

_Metadata in  the latest https://github.com/OP-TED/ePO/blob/master/implementation/ePO_core/owl_ontology/ePO_core.ttl[_ePO_core.ttl] file._

If any errors or bugs are encountered, the Product Owner informs the Development Team, and the Development Team fixes these errors by re-doing all the business processes of the Workflow from the “ORSD consolidation” Business Process, to the “Dev Team internal review” Business Process. Note that during this fixing of errors the “ePO Working Group Meeting” Business Process is omitted since the changes to the Ontology are purely technical. However, if there is a problem in the conventions this might require the WG to confirm what was meant by the wrong convention to allow it to be corrected.

If no errors are found during the “Product Owner internal review (CM repository)” Business Process, then the “*Product Owner accepts pull request to release branch in the CM repository and creates a tag.*” Business Process takes place. During this Process, the Product Owner accepts the pull request, and creates a tag on the release branch of the https://github.com/OP-TED/epo-conceptual-model[ OP-TED/ePO-conceptual-model] repository.


== Application and Technology view

The diagram below describes all the artefacts involved in this stage using business (yellow), application (blue) and technology (green) layers. The GitHub Repository branch that is used for this stage is also depicted as an orange rectangle for reference purposes.
 Note that here we do not explain purposes of Artefacts, but we describe what is produced and how. The actual description of the produced Artefacts is provided xref:SDS and related artefacts/SDSmodel2owl.adoc[here].




image::preparing SDS version release [concise].bmp[]
_Application and Technology Layers of the “Preparing Semantic Data Specification Version Release” stage_


All the generated artefacts are stored on the version specific release branch of the https://github.com/OP-TED/epo-conceptual-model[GitHub OP-TED/epo-conceptual-model] repository.

* The “XMI UML Model” Data Object represents the “Conceptual Model (exchangeable)” Business Object. Currently the version of the XMI/UML that is being exported from the EA file is 2.5.1 and is used as input for the following model2owl application components:
** The “model2owl formal artefacts generator” Application Component that generates the “SDS formal artefact” Data Object.
*** The “SDS formal artefact” Data Object realises  the “SDS documentation” Business Object. As seen in the diagram below, the “SDS formal artefact” is a Generalisation of the following Data Objects:

**** The “Owl-core” Data Object realises  the “Lightweight Ontology (for interoperability)” Business Object and represents the MODULE_NAME.OWL/.ttl ontology file for any given module. Each file contains the OWL Ontology Concepts of a specific module as well as the deprecated concepts for that module.
**** The “Owl-restrictions” Data Object realises  the “Ontology Axiomatization (for inference)” business Object and represents the MODULE_NAME_restrictions.rdf/.ttl ontology restrictions file for any given module. Each file contains the OWL Ontology restrictions such as cardinalities and range of properties for a specific module.
**** The “SHACL-shapes” Data Object realises the “Application Profile (for interoperability)” business Object and represents the MODULE_NAME_shapes.rdf/.TTL shapes ontology file for any given module.

image::SDS formal artefacts.bmp[]
_The “SDS formal artefact” Data Object._


** The “model2owl documentation generator” Application Component that generates a part of the “SDS human-readable artefact” Data Object.
*** The “SDS human-readable artefact” Data Object realises  the “SDS documentation” Business Object.
**** The “SDS human-readable artefact” is a Generalisation of the “XMI based reference document (web optimised)” Data Object that realises  the “SDS reference document (glossaries)” Business Object. The “XMI based reference document (web optimised)” Data Object represents the glossary .html page for any given module and is automatically generated by model2owl.
**** As seen in the diagram below, the “SDS human-readable artefact” is also a generalisation of other Data Objects that are not created by model2owl, such as the print and web versions of the ORSD and the Release notes that are created manually by the Development Team, and the CM diagrams as websites generated automatically by EA,



image::2024-12-19_11-52.png[]
_The “SDS human-readable artefact” Data Object. The specialisations marked in purple are not generated by model2owl._



** The “model2owl validator” Application Component that generates the “Automated assessment artefact” Data Object.
*** The “Automated assessment artefact” Data Object realises  the “Quality assessment reports” Business Object. As seen in the diagram below, the “Automated assessment artefact” is a Generalisation of the following Data Objects:

**** The “SHACL conformance report” Data Object realises  part of the “Quality assessment reports” Business Object and presents the results of the validation of a specific module using SHACL shapes.
**** The “UML checkers conformance report” Data Object realises  part of the “Quality assessment reports” Business Object and presents the results of the validation of a specific module by using UML conversion checkers.


image::data:image/png;base64,[]


_The “Automated assessment artefact” Data Object._


** The “model2owl differ” Application Component that generates the “Automated evolution artefact” Data Object.
*** The “Automated evolution artefact” Data Object realises  the “SDS evolution documentation” Business Object. As seen in the diagram below, the “Automated evolution artefact” Data Object is a Generalisation of the following Data Objects:
**** The “Change Notes” Data Object realises  the “Change Notes” Business Object and contains all the concept changes that happened between the last release and this release in a human-readable web page format.
**** The “OWL-core diff report” Data Object realises  the “SDS diffing report” Business Object and contains the difference between the MODULE_NAME.rdf/.ttl files of the last release and this release for any given module.
**** The “OWL-restriction diff report” Data Object realises  the “SDS diffing report” Business Object and contains the difference between the MODULE_NAME_restrictions.rdf/.ttl files of the last release and this release for any given module.
**** The “SHACL diff report” Data Object realises  the “SDS diffing report” Business Object and contains the difference between the MODULE_NAME_shapes.rdf/.ttl files of the last release and this release for any given module.

As seen on the diagram below, each application component is part of the model2owl service suite. When a GitHub Action is triggered in the https://github.com/OP-TED/model2owl[OP-TED/model2owl] repository, a specific GitHub Action script is run, and according to it, a specific model2owl application component will run for a specific module on the version specific release branch of the https://github.com/OP-TED/epo-conceptual-model[GitHub OP-TED/epo-conceptual-model repository,] making use of the SDS Generation Configuration files for that module, and generating the files mentioned previously in this section.

== Automated Semantic Data Specification generation and validation


Automated SDS development shall be adopted as the https://semiceu.github.io/style-guide/1.0.0/index.html[SEMIC style guide]  suggests: Using the UML Conceptual model as a https://semiceu.github.io/style-guide/1.0.0/gc-conceptual-model-conventions.html#sec:cmc-r1[Single Source of Truth] principle, and automatically generating the SDS from the UML. For the purposes of automatic generation, we use https://github.com/OP-TED/model2owl[model2owl] tool, described in section 4. Following the https://interoperable-europe.ec.europa.eu/collection/semic-support-centre/application-profiles-what-are-they-and-how-model-and-reuse-them-properly-look-through-dcat-ap[SEMIC blog articles,]  it is clear that automation is needed for all points of the UML transformation to SDS artefacts, and manual transformations should be discouraged and avoided at all costs, as SDS artefacts that are generated manually will often display inconsistencies between them, and the Single Source of Truth.
